            <h2 class="text-left section-header mb-4">The top 10</h2>
                <p class="paragraph--dark text-left font-size-1">This is the easiest part of trading to understand, but probably the hardest 
                to implement.  Without a good set of rules and your edge, your days as a trader are numbered.</p>

           <ol class="terms-list">
            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"><strong>Stop Losses:</strong></span> 
            <span class="font-size-1">Before entering a trade, set a stop loss - no more than 5 to 7% of the 
            total trade.  Allow some room for a shake out, but if the stop loss level is hit, 
            <strong>sell the position without hesitation.</strong>  Your first loss is the best loss.  Limit your losses, and never wait 
            for a position to 'get back'.  </span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">If a stock has been purchased, and runs up quickly, take some 
            off the table.  Size the position so that even if the stock returns to a new break-even stop loss, your total trade is still 
            larger than your average winning trade. <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Don't chase stocks. Don't listen to the media.  As soon as CNBC starts 
            hawking their shit, and getting CEOs on the air, that is a good sign to get out if you own it.  Or fuck it, short it. <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> Don't fuck around with options.  Trust me, I've tried.<span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Unless you have a huge gain in a stock, don't hold the entire position 
            through earnings.  Don't initiate a position before earnings unless you are a degenerate gambler.  Seriously...<span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">The market doesn't owe you anything.  It will extract the maximum 
            amount of money while inflicting an infinite amount of frustration and mental anguish.  If your trades are working, stick 
            with your system and don't get cocky.  If your trades are not working, close out your positions and go take a trip.  I like to drive up to 
            Montreal.<span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Don't try to justify "why" moves in the market happen.  Often times, news, headlines, and 
            opinions are smoke screens for market makers to buy or sell.  Follow the price and volume signals at all times.   <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Your friend's stock tips suck. Don't follow them.  And their record isn't as good as they say. 
            be careful about listening to anyone who only boasts about winners.  Ideally listen to your own judgement, or of people with proven track records, 
            and very strong knowledge of the markets...if you can find them.  <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Hope is not a risk management strategy.  If your trade sucks, and you are hoping for it to come back
            , close out the position and do something else.  <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Let your winners run, and cut your losers fast.  Most people will 
            take profits on a winner, and keep holding onto a loser hoping that the loser will turn into a winner.  This is your ego protecting itself. 
            If you want ego, come to jacksons landing during the winter and skate in the sunday morning session.  otherwise, leave the ego at the door 
            if you want to trade.   <span></li>
            
            </ol>
