            <h2 class="text-left section-header mb-4 text-center"">My System</h2>
                <p class="paragraph--dark text-left font-size-1">My system consists mostly of technicals, aka charts as well as fundamentals. The 
                charts are a schematic of the supply and demand of shares being traded.  It is this supply and demand, as well as the bid/ask of the stock 
                which will move the stock up or down.  The fundamentals lend themselves well for longer term trades, 
                as a thematic catalyst ( new product, earnings expansion, new management, etc) 
                can propel a stock for a long period of time.   </p>

                <p class="paragraph--dark text-left font-size-1">Here is the basics.
                </p>

           <ol class="terms-list">
         
            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Overview - Read Bill O'Niel's book "How to Make Money In Stocks".  
             <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Fundamentals - I look for earnings and sales growth on a quarterly basis.  I want to 
            see accelerating (increasing rate of change) of year over year comps for earnings.  Earnings must be sustainable, and long lasting for example from 
            a new product, or a new catalyst for demand for said products.   <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> Insider buying - Execs buying large blocks of shares.  If execs own very little ,and collect 
            fat paychecks, they are probably pieces of shit just like their companies.  Also look for high instituional sponsorship.  If these guys are buying, so will I.    <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1">Charts - I buy when a stock breaks out of a definitive trading range.  I look for 
            low volume on distirbution, and higher volume during accumulation.  The stock must have good volume when it exits a trading range. Read books on the subject 
            to get the idea.  See below for Qualcom, a very strong performing stock during the 1999 dot com bubble <span></li>

            <%= image_tag "stock-qcom.png", alt: "QCOM breakout", class: 'picture-1' %>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> Indicators - I use price, volume and volatility.  I do not use fancy technical mumbo jumbo 
            like MACD, Fib retracements, or any of that.  Price, price levels, and the number of shares traded...and thats it! <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> Moving averages - I use a few moving averages to determine what other traders might do.
            Usually they act as areas of resistance or support for a stock.  They aren't the be all, end all but I will use them as a simple stop-loss or entries.
            <span></li>

            <li class="text-left font-size-1"><span class="font-size-1"> New product - This one is big. Find an earnings winner which has a new product, new service, or 
            new industry.  Even if the fundamentals are garbage, watch the charts.  These companies can attract a lot of instiutional sponsorship.  
            <span></li>

        
            
            </ol>
